            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRFRIGHTENEDWASTHEPREACHER">&#x201C;But frightened was the preacher when&#x201D;
                    (&#x201C;Highland Music&#x201D;)</title></head>
                <!--An apparatus may contain all or only some of the following sections.-->
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section">Title</head>
                    <p>This brief, untitled poem, included in a New Year&#x02BC;s greeting (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><title type="book" corresp="#RFL">RFL</title></ref>, 170&#x2013;71),
                        is called &#x201C;Highland Music&#x201D; by <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>,</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p>PML (MA 3451).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p>31 December,</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition &#x0026; Publication</head>
                    <p>Published in <title type="book" corresp="#JRPOEMS8D1891">PJR (1891?, 8<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>)</title>, 1:271; and <title type="book" corresp="#RFL">RFL</title>, 171. Facsimiled in <title type="book" corresp="#JRPOEMS8D1891">PJR
                        (1891?, 8<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>)</title>, vol. 1, between pp. 18 and 19; and <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE">Works</title>, vol. 2, facing p.
                        265.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <p><persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName>, who connects it with <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s versification of <persName corresp="#WS">Scott</persName>&#x02BC;s <title type="book" corresp="#SCOTTMONASTERY"><hi rend="italic">The
                        Monastery</hi></title> (no. 46), referring the reader to chapter 35. No such episode
                        occurs in that chapter, and, in any case, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s versification never
                        extended beyond the opening chapters of the novel. Still more mysteriously,
                        <persName corresp="#WGC">Collingwood</persName> quotes a &#x201C;note in his father&#x02BC;s handwriting:&#x2014;&#x2018;See <title type="series" corresp="#SCOTTCANONGATE">Chronicles of
                        the Canongate</title>; the Flute &#x0026; Drum &#x0026; Bagpipe; the latter having no
                        beauty.&#x2019;&#x201D; No such note by <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> has been found with the manuscript, and
                        <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName>&#x02BC;s reference is equally illusive, <persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName> having failed to locate it
                        in any of the <title type="series" corresp="#SCOTTCANONGATE">Chronicles of the Canongate</title> novels (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><title type="book" corresp="#RFL">RFL</title></ref>, 171 n. 2).</p>
                    <p>The poem&#x02BC;s echoing martial music seems to dovetail with the end of no. 33,
                        adapted from <persName corresp="#WS">Scott</persName>&#x02BC;s <title type="book" corresp="#SCOTTWAVERLEY"><hi rend="italic">Waverley</hi></title>. No &#x201C;frightened preacher&#x201D; hears the &#x201C;music of
                        the clans&#x201D; in that novel, but <persName type="fictional" corresp="#EDWARDWAVERLEY">Edward</persName> listens to the bagpipes of the
                        retreating <geogName corresp="#SCOTTISHHIGHLANDS">Highland</geogName> forces, from which he has been cut off. Perhaps <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>
                        was thinking of <persName type="fictional" corresp="#EDWARDWAVERLEY">Edward</persName>&#x02BC;s disguise as a divinity student in the next chapter.
                        If so, and this poem forms part of the versification of <title type="book" corresp="#SCOTTWAVERLEY"><hi rend="italic">Waverley</hi></title> in no. 33,
                        it may have originally been intended as text for a puppet performance of the
                        battle (see no. 35).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="TEXTUALNOTE">
                    <head type="section">Textual Note</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
